Individual Technology Adoption Strategy Proposal
Wisconsin Maritime Museum
I. Introduction
This proposal aims to support users of the Wisconsin Maritime Museum in analyzing
the data available in its online collection. The museums main goal is to engage and
educate the public in topics related to the Great Lakes, Wisconsins maritime history,
and ships. This proposal focuses on the development of a tool which uses web scraping
and geocoding technologies in Python to create visualizations of the online collection
metadata, including maps with the location of photographs.
II. Institutional profile
The Wisconsin Maritime Museum is an institution located in Manitowoc, in the state of
Wisconsin, United States. It was created in 1969 initially, its name was Manitowoc
Submarine Memorial Association. Focused on the maritime history of Wisconsin and
the Great Lakes, the museum attracts a significant number of visitors. As shown in their
2023 report, more than 30,000 people visited the museum
1
. The staff comprises 11
employees, not including volunteers, and the board of trustees has 12 members.
The institutions main activities are exhibits, field trips, and outreach events. Users
include students, researchers, and people interested in the subject. Even though each
group of users has specific data needs, this tool could help researchers focus on specific
metadata fields, such as Place, to understand what they could use from the collection,
and most documented places, for instance. It could also be useful for the general public
to consume information in a more visual way, without too many details that could be
overwhelming.
The online collection has a fraction of the museums collection, with a strong emphasis
on photographs. Each photograph record has its own metadata. Not all fields are
complete in each of the items, but it is still a significant amount of information
available, which is crucial for researchers. Data types encountered in the online
1
hps://www.wisconsinmarime.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Annual-Report-2023.pptx
collection are strings for the following fields: description, search terms, object name,
and people. The field date is usually a full date, although sometimes the date will be a
year, or an approximate date, written as a string. Similarly, the field accession generally
denotes the accession date, but sometimes it can be an id in a string format.
The development of a tool that could use all of these formats is crucial for the users, but
it would also require skilled employees to create it. There is a need to work with
incomplete dates, and fields with different data types, among others.
III. Technology Overview
In order to understand the information regarding the museums online collection of
photographs, there is a need to access all of the metadata fields and be able to sort the
ones we are interested in. Web scraping is a great tool to accomplish this, as it allows us
to extract data from websites.
This proposals tool aims to gather the photographs metadata and use location data to
create maps. It would help researchers to see the geographic information from a new
perspective, and it could possibly bring some new questions that would not come up
through the visualization of one photograph at a time, such as What are the most
documented areas in the museums photograph collection?. This would help to fulfill
one of the declared purposes of the museum, which is to create personal and
meaningful connections with our waterways
2
. It is interesting to analyze the big picture
of the collection, to understand its strengths and weaknesses the lack of information is
also information.
IV. Issues of power / Power mitigation
This tool can be used to understand the strengths of the collection, such as the items,
eras, persons or places that are more documented. It can also be used to understand the
weaknesses of the collection, or what information is missing. Potential bias resulting
from this tool is that, since some of the items lack specific metadata fields, it would be a
not completely accurate portrait of the collection. If this technology is used for the
2
hps://www.wisconsinmarime.org/about-us/
purposes of analyzing the people in the photographs, for instance, it would also result in
biased information, as there are photographs where they are not identified. Another
issue is the occurrence of counties and cities with the same name (initially, the code
understands as the county).
One way to address this question is to have all of this information well documented in a
datasheet. An adaptation of the model presented by Gebru, Timnit et al. (2021) would be
a good solution, with emphasis on what is missing and why.
The Date field can also result in biased information, as the dates mentioned are not
standardized (some variations are the year, the full date, circa, etc). This tool could be
adjusted to focus only on years, for instance.
V. The Code
The initial part of the code is web scraping. For this proposal, the first 20 results of the
Photograph section in the Online Collection were used.
Image 1
BeautifulSoup is used to extract specific HTML data. In this case, we need to extract the
URLs of the photographs displayed.
Image 2

Image 3
With the URLs, it is possible to extract the metadata from each photograph.
Image 4
To make it possible to gather the data from the Place field, it helps to have it as column.
Image 5
The next step is to identify the unique places that appear in the list.
Image 6
Finally, we enter the places on a map.
Image 7
This proposal could be extended to other metadata fields, such as date. It would be
possible to analyze the historical periods that are represented, and when those
photographs joined the museums collection. Another interesting field to be analyzed in
such a way is people, which would allow users to analyze the representativeness of
women, for example. Depending on the data, it might be possible to do text analysis to
also identify professions associated with the persons, which might reveal whether crew
or sponsors are relatively more represented in the collection.
